recordings.rmk:
Ed Pandolfino's analysis is copy-and-pasted below:

===========================================

It all fits perfectly well as S. c. nelsoni.
 
As you say, the first (faint) vocalization from the 'other' bird is typical nelsoni "disyllabic quank", using the terminology of Pandolfino & Pieplow. All the vocalizations from the second bird are song notes. The pitch of the first several song bouts are in 805-825 Hz range (measuring as difference between successive partials). Right in the typical range for nelsoni (788 +/- 126) and a good bit higher than carolinensis (604 +/- 97) although we did measure one carolinensis song at just over 900Hz. Those single or double notes you refer to are song notes, same pitch and duration, NOT the modulated quanks of carolinensis which are longer and show very distinct frequency modulation. I have found that all of the subspecies sometimes give one or just a few song notes in between song sequences on occasion. There is that point, as you note, where the bird speeds up the rate AND increases the pitch (to about 950Hz) for a couple of song sequences. The rate for the first several songs is right around 7 notes/sec, the 'fast' sequences jumps up to over 8/sec. However, the bird then goes back to singing at the same pitch and rate as before. We found at least a couple examples of single individuals switching to af faster song rate (even doubling the rate) and speculated that it may be related to level of agitation. However, we didn't see a corresponding increase in pitch to go along with the rate change, so that is interesting.
 
So the pitch in consistent with nelsoni and there are none of the diagnostic modulated quanks that would indicate carolinensis in this.

recordings.rmk:
Besides the commonly-heard single soft contact calls, these two nuthatches were giving two and three-note calls (peer-peer, peer-peer-peer) that closely resemble the "keer" calls described by Pieplow (2017) for the eastern subspecies (S. c. carolinensis). He describes this as "infrequent, by both sexes in courtship and high excitement", which fits perfectly with the context I observed. Two birds interacting closely, then chasing each other with this call increasing in intensity during the chase. Its a call I have heard a few times from this Pacific subspecies, but never before managed to get a recording.

Pieplow describes the eastern subspecies' "keer" call as "seminasal" but in this case, I see no indication of nasal tone (just clear harmonics) and also sounded non-nasal to the ear.

recordings.rmk: For quite some time (more than 10 years now, actually), the carolinensis subspecies of the White-breasted Nuthatch has been reported from the back end (the west end) of the Walden/Sawhill complex. I'm not aware that any recordings have been made of the bird or birds at the site, so here is my effort. This particular bird wasn't especially vocal, but its call notes were of the "yarnk" and "yarnk, yarnk" variety characteristic of carolinensis. recordings.loc: Poway, San Diego County, California
recordings.rmk: There was at least one Nuthatch seen on the bird-watching trip today.  The one in the recording was first seen near the trail junction between Blue Sky and Lake Poway, and it proceeded down the trail at roughly the same pace as me, then began foraging in the eucalyptus tree at the end of the trail where it leads out of the forest and towards Lake Ramona.  It's possible there were two individuals on the trail because I thought I could vaguely hear another one calling off in the distance towards Lake Poway, but I was not certain.  The individual in this recording may very well be the same one I had been repeatedly seeing for the past couple weeks at Lake Poway.  Normally that bird is seen at Lake Poway in the evening, then by sundown, flies towards Blue Sky.
